    <h2>How 3-Character .com Domains Are Valued</h2>

    <p>Three-character .com domains are finite assets. The namespace is fixed — no new 3-character combinations can be created. As digital presence becomes increasingly important for businesses worldwide, the supply of premium short domains remains constant while demand grows.</p>

    <p>Buyers and brokers consistently evaluate short .com domains against a common set of factors:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Length</strong> — shorter domains command higher prices. Three characters is near the minimum for a meaningful .com</li>
      <li><strong>Pattern</strong> — the industry classifies 3-character .coms by pattern: LLL (three letters), LLN, LNN, NLL, NNL, LNL, NLN. Each pattern has its own market dynamics</li>
      <li><strong>Character quality</strong> — common letters (A, E, I, N, O, R, S, T) and premium digits (1, 2, 3) carry higher value than obscure letters (Q, X, Z) or the digit 0</li>
      <li><strong>Meaning</strong> — domains that form recognizable words, industry terms, or technical vocabulary are valued far above random strings. A domain that is already in daily use as a word outperforms a semantically empty one</li>
      <li><strong>Extension</strong> — .com remains the most trusted and valuable TLD by a significant margin</li>
      <li><strong>Age</strong> — continuous registration history adds trust and authority</li>
      <li><strong>Clean history</strong> — domains without spam, malware, or penalty history carry their full potential</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Public sale data is intentionally sparse — most short-domain transactions close under NDA. Researchers typically consult <a href="https://namebio.com/" rel="noopener">NameBio</a> and <a href="https://www.dnjournal.com/" rel="noopener">DNJournal</a> for the subset of sales that are reported. What those databases consistently show is that the combination of scarcity, .com extension, and embedded meaning is what separates ordinary short domains from premium ones.</p>

